<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the THREE `sys_choice` rows
    that enumerate the legal values of the `status` Choice field on the
    `x_[scope]_case_task` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim) for x_[scope]_case_task:

        Field    Type     Constraints
        status   Choice   Open, In Progress, Closed

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning):
        choices/sys_choice_case_task_status.xml -> Open, In Progress, Closed
        case_task.status default = Open

    The values authored here are the EXHAUSTIVE, CLOSED enumeration that the
    AAP mandates - exactly three records, no more and no fewer. Per the
    MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE in AAP Section 0.7.2, additional statuses such as
    `On Hold`, `Cancelled`, `Pending Review`, `Complete`, `Done`, etc. are
    explicitly out of scope. ArkCase's Activiti BPM engine carried a much
    larger task-status vocabulary (ASSIGNED, IN_PROGRESS, COMPLETE, CLOSED,
    DELETE, NOT_STARTED, IN_REVIEW, PENDING_APPROVAL, etc.) tied to BPMN
    process variables; the POC scope (AAP Section 0.3.2) explicitly excludes
    BPMN/Activiti, buckslip, and any approval-routing capability, so the
    target collapses the entire fragmented free-form String vocabulary into
    these three controlled labels.

    THIS CHOICE LIST IS THE LINCHPIN OF THE CASE-RESOLUTION GUARD.
    Per AAP Section 0.5.5 ("In Progress -> Resolved: All linked
    x_[scope]_case_task records have status = Closed") and AAP Section
    0.7.4 verbatim, the case state-machine flow surfaces the literal
    blocking error message
        "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
    when ANY child task on the case has status != Closed. The query that
    drives the gate, executed by ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml
    and by the canTransitionToResolved() static method on
    ../script_includes/x_[scope]_CaseTransitionValidator.xml, is:

        var gr = new GlideRecord('x_[scope]_case_task');
        gr.addQuery('case', current.sys_id);
        gr.addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed');
        gr.setLimit(1);
        gr.query();
        if (gr.next()) {
            // Block the transition and surface the AAP Section 0.7.4
            // verbatim blocking error message on the form.
        }

    The query string literal `'Closed'` MUST byte-match the choice value
    authored in Record 3 below; any divergence (e.g., "CLOSED", "closed",
    "Done", "Complete") would silently let cases resolve while open work
    remained, defeating the AAP Section 0.7.3 workflow validation gate.

    Per AAP Sections 0.5.5 and 0.5.2, the labels declared here are read by:

      Two Flow Designer subflows that gate parent-case transitions:
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_resolved_transition.xml
            (queries `status != Closed` against this Choice list)
        ../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml
            (consults task counts indirectly when displaying open-tasks
            warnings on the parent case form)

      One Script Include exposing reusable transition guards used by both
      flows and business rules:
        ../script_includes/x_[scope]_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
            (canTransitionToResolved() iterates child tasks via the
            same GlideRecord query against this Choice list)

      Two reports rendered as Agent Workspace dashboard widgets:
        ../reports/x_[scope]_my_overdue_tasks.xml
            (list filtered by `due_date < javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(0)
            AND status != Closed AND assigned_to = javascript:gs.getUserID()`;
            the `status != Closed` clause uses the exact Title Case label
            declared in Record 3 below. Closed tasks are deliberately
            excluded from the overdue list because a finished task cannot
            be overdue regardless of when its due_date fell.)

      Synthetic demo task seed records satisfying AAP Section 0.4.1
      minimum-data threshold ("at least one open and one closed task per
      demo case in `In Progress` or `Pending` state, to exercise the
      all-tasks-closed gate"):
        ../seed-data/tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_*.xml
            (mix of Open and Closed labels deterministically exercises
            the case-resolution gate during fresh-PDI re-import
            validation per AAP Section 0.7.3)

      The idempotent server-side seed script:
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
            (writes synthetic task status labels via
            GlideRecord.setValue('status', 'Open'|'In Progress'|'Closed'))

    THE VERBATIM BLOCKING-ERROR MESSAGE from AAP Section 0.7.4 references
    Record 3's label by Title Case string-equality comparison:
        - "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          (fires when a Resolved transition is attempted while any child
           task has status != Closed - compares against the Title Case
           label declared in Record 3 below)

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java line 81:
            private String status;
        ArkCase's task `status` was a free-form String field on the
        AcmTask domain object. The field carried NO Bean Validation
        constraints (no @Size, no @NotNull, no @Pattern), so any
        caller could assign any string (despite implementing
        AcmStatefulEntity at AcmTask.java line 33 / 61) and the JPA /
        Activiti layer enforced no enumeration. ArkCase's task-status
        vocabulary was distributed across BPMN process variables and
        Activiti ProcessInstance state; the legal labels included
        ASSIGNED, IN_PROGRESS, COMPLETE, CLOSED, DELETE, NOT_STARTED,
        and several engine-internal identifiers. The ServiceNow
        target replaces this fragmented free-form String with a
        controlled Choice vocabulary of three labels (Open, In Progress,
        Closed) through the parent dictionary entry's
        `<choice>3</choice>` setting plus the sibling sys_choice
        records below. AAP Section 0.1.2 codifies this kind of free-
        form-String -> Choice tightening as the ServiceNow-side
        equivalent of ArkCase's bean-validation enforcement.
      - AcmTask.java line 82 also declared `private String pendingStatus;`
        which ArkCase used as a transient sub-state holder while a
        task was being routed through buckslip approvals. The
        ServiceNow target intentionally OMITS pendingStatus because
        the POC scope (AAP Section 0.3.2) explicitly excludes
        BPMN/Activiti, buckslip, and any approval-routing capability;
        all transient state is collapsed back into the single `status`
        Choice. This is consistent with the AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim
        case_task field set, which lists status as the sole lifecycle
        column.
      - The three AAP-mandated values represent a minimal task lifecycle:
            Open        - task created, awaiting work
            In Progress - agent actively working
            Closed      - task completed (or cancelled, but POC
                          deliberately does not distinguish; canceled
                          tasks are also Closed for the resolution-gate
                          check)

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - EXACTLY three records: no fewer, no more. Per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The three records below are the COMPLETE enumeration
        for this POC. Tasks in this POC are simple work items - they do
        not have a Draft pre-state (every task is created Open and
        immediately visible to its assignee), they do not have a Pending
        sub-state (a task that is paused remains "In Progress" with the
        work simply not advancing), and they do not have a Resolved-but-
        not-Closed half-state (closing a task is a single atomic step
        performed by the assignee).
      - Title Case labels: `Open`, `In Progress`, `Closed`. NOT uppercase
        (which ArkCase used legacy-style: ASSIGNED, IN_PROGRESS, COMPLETE,
        CLOSED), NOT lowercase, NOT camelCase. The agent prompt's "Most
        common error point" warning specifically calls out: `In Progress`
        is TWO words separated by a SINGLE ASCII space - NOT `InProgress`
        (no separator), NOT `In_Progress` (snake_case underscore), NOT
        `IN PROGRESS` (uppercase shout-case), NOT `In  Progress` (double
        space). Likewise `Closed` is single-word Title Case - NOT
        `CLOSED` and NOT `closed`.
      - Label = Value pattern: each `<value>` matches its sibling
        `<label>` byte-for-byte. The stored value IS the human-readable
        label - no integer state codes, no enum ordinals, no separate
        machine-key. This is a standard ServiceNow Choice-field idiom
        and matches the pattern used by the sibling Choice list in this
        app for x_[scope]_case.status (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed) in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml. The
        intentional naming overlap on the `Open`, `In Progress`, and
        `Closed` labels means cross-table reports can render a unified
        "Status" column header without per-table label aliasing.
      - Sequence ordering by lifecycle progression in increments of 100:
            Open (100) -> In Progress (200) -> Closed (300)
        This matches the natural narrative arc of a task's life and
        drives:
            (a) the dropdown order on the case_task form
            (b) the slice/bar order on any future task-status reports
            (c) the lifecycle visualization intuition for end users
            (d) the future extensibility - increment-of-100 spacing
                leaves room for inserting new statuses without
                renumbering (e.g., a hypothetical `Cancelled` could
                slot at sequence 250 between In Progress and Closed),
                though the AAP MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE prohibits adding
                any in this POC.
      - All three records are <inactive>false</inactive>: every value
        is active and selectable in the dropdown. There are no
        deprecated legacy values to filter out (this is a greenfield
        Choice list).
      - No <dependent_value/>: status is a TOP-LEVEL lifecycle
        indicator whose legal values do NOT depend on `type`,
        `assigned_to`, `due_date`, the parent case's status, or any
        other field. The dependent_value mechanism is for declarative
        cascading at the form-rendering level only; runtime validation
        of which transitions are legal lives in the parent-case state-
        machine flows and the CaseTransitionValidator script include.
      - No <hint/>: the labels are self-documenting (Open, In Progress,
        Closed are universally understood task-management terms). The
        agent prompt explicitly suppresses helper text per the POC
        scope.
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every record's `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve into the `x_[scope]`
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-
        scope writes - the OOB tables sys_user, sys_user_group,
        sys_user_role, core_company, task, incident, etc. are never
        modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]`), not by literal sys_id. Each
        record's `<sys_id>` element value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key - computed as MD5 of the canonical
        identifier `x_[scope]_case_task.status.<Value>` so that re-
        generation of this XML yields byte-identical output (no random
        UUIDs). This is the same derivation pattern used by the sibling
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml file. The sys_id is NOT
        a reference to any other record.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP
        convention; the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App
        Engine Studio creation time, which the import process resolves
        into the final scope namespace.
      - English language only: `<language>en</language>` on every
        record per the POC scope. The platform supports localization
        via additional sys_choice records keyed by `language`, but
        no non-English locales are in scope.
      - `<sys_domain>global</sys_domain>` on every record: domain
        separation is not used by this scoped application.
      - No PII: the labels are categorical lifecycle terms only; no
        real names, email addresses, or organizational identifiers
        are derived from or stored in these records.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped application)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_task.xml (parent table; status field's
          host)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_task_status.xml (parent dictionary
          entry; declares the column shape, choice=3,
          default_value=Open, mandatory=true. Without this entry the
          sys_choice records below have no column to attach to. Per
          line 297-300 of the dictionary file, this Choice list MUST
          load AFTER the dictionary entry.)

      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD BEFORE all consumers enumerated above
      (subflow validate_resolved_transition, CaseTransitionValidator
      script include, my_overdue_tasks report, demo seed-data tasks,
      and seed_demo_data.js). Loading order is enforced by the
      alphabetical Update Set preview ordering plus the record-by-
      record dependency-resolution pass.

    Source for the deterministic sys_id derivations:
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.status.Open"        | md5sum
            => db2d244d7bce6bd6a9b0984fa4f67d66
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.status.In Progress" | md5sum
            => 3127c03954bedb860746122fdb78d244
        echo -n "x_[scope]_case_task.status.Closed"      | md5sum
            => 3e06456307a50567a8aaf02e62bda209

    The MD5 input is the canonical identifier <table>.<element>.<value>,
    matching the same derivation pattern used by the sibling
    ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml file. The MD5 derivation
    guarantees that re-generation of this Update Set on any agent run
    produces byte-identical sys_ids (no random UUIDs), which is required
    for clean Update-Set re-import on a fresh PDI without creating
    duplicate sys_choice rows.
-->
<unload unload_date="2025-01-01 00:00:00">
<sys_choice action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
    <dependent_value/>
    <element>status</element>
    <hint/>
    <inactive>false</inactive>
    <label>Open</label>
    <language>en</language>
    <name>x_[scope]_case_task</name>
    <sequence>100</sequence>
    <sys_class_name>sys_choice</sys_class_name>
    <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
    <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
    <sys_domain>global</sys_domain>
    <sys_id>db2d244d7bce6bd6a9b0984fa4f67d66</sys_id>
    <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
